Message: 6
Date: Mon, 06 Jan 2003 14:01:07 -0500
From: Marshall Booth <mbooth+@pitt.edu>
Organization: University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine
To: "Mailshell User" <nospam@mailshell.com>
Subject: Re: [Mercedes] glow plug circuit

Glow plugs decay and fail just as any resistor (an incandescent light
bulb is a good example) fails after some number of thermal cycles. So a
plug may last for many thousands of starting cycles, but WILL eventually
fail. In 61x series diesels using parallel plugs, 150-250kmi lifetimes
are common for the original Bosch or Beru plugs (newer diesels with
"afterstart" glow plug function seem to deliver about 25% of that
lifetime, presumably because the plugs are on MUCH longer for every cold
start). Most non-OEM replacements that I know of are substantially
inferior to the Bosch or Beru replacments and can fail within a few
months or just a few years. The OEM plugs cost about $10 each from many
distributors (I know that Rusty has them in that range). 

Plugs should be torqued to 20 Nm (15 ft-lb) and you can use a dab of
anti-sieze on the plug (but it is seldom necessary). If the plug is
shrouded in carbon inside the prechamber, the plug will not work
optimally and will fail prematurely. My rule of thumb is that if the old
plug must be wiggle and yanked to be removed, then the prechamber area
needs to be reamed with a glow plug reamer. In the absence of a proper
reamer, I know of people using a dowel or an old plug with the heating
element flatened to "ream" out the prechamber and they claim they work
fine. On the only occasion that I needed a reamer and didn't have one, I
pulled the injector and cleaned the prechamber from above and the blew
it out by cranking the engine over a few times with the injector (or
glow plug) out and the injection pump shutoff held down. That worked FOR
ME. 

Marshall 
