From: Sixto Orosa <tabijan@yahoo.com>
To: "Mailshell User" <nospam@mailshell.com>
Subject: [Mercedes] OM603 - strange results from glow plug test

I found a dead glow plug in the SDL but the process of
finding it raises some questions.

I tested the resistance to ground of each pin at the
relay.  #1, #2, #5 and #6 showed 1.7 ohms, #4 showed
6.6 ohms (dead), and #3 showed 1.500 ohms.

Question 1 - I'm using a very basic Radio Shack DVM. 
Why does it read 01.7 for the 4 good plugs, 06.6 for
the bad plug and 1.500 consistently for #3?  Why does
it change the display format for only that plug?  I
was thinking it's part of the auto scaling function,
but the 1.7 ohm readings fluctuate between 1.6 and 1.8
staying most of the time at 1.7.  I figure it there's
scaling, that's where it would give me more digits.

I also tested the resistance to ground of the plug
terminals.  #1 showed 1.7 ohms, I couldn't get my
probe on #2, #3 showed 1.500 ohms, #4 showed 6.6 ohms,
#5 showed 2.0 ohms and #6 showed 1.3 ohms.  The
connector was off the relay.

Question 2 - If I put my probes together, I get 1.4
ohms.  How could I get 1.3 ohms through the #6 plug?

I'm using the cheapest DVM I could find so I shouldn't
be surprised at questionable results.  I'd like to
understand why the results aren't random.  Each test
yields the same results everytime I try.

Yes, I'm getting a new set of plugs.

Thanks,
Sixto
91 300SE
87 300SDL
83 300SD


